Step one — Grayscale Conversion
So the image that comes in from the camera is a color image. Specifically it's stored in BGR format — that's Blue, Green, Red — which is just how OpenCV handles images by default. Every single pixel in that image is actually three numbers: one for how much blue is in it, one for green, one for red.
Now, color sounds useful, but for what we're trying to do — find edges, detect shapes, analyze geometry — color is mostly irrelevant noise. A license plate edge looks like an edge whether it's a white plate on a red car or a yellow plate on a black car. What actually matters is the contrast in brightness, not the hue.
So we collapse those three numbers into one by computing a weighted average. The formula is Y = 0.299·R + 0.587·G + 0.114·B. Notice green gets the biggest weight. That's because human vision — and by extension, most camera sensors — is most sensitive to green light. So green carries the most useful luminance information. Blue gets the smallest weight because it contributes the least to perceived brightness.
After this step, every pixel is just a single number between 0 and 255. Zero is black, 255 is white, everything in between is a shade of gray. We've gone from a three-layer image to a one-layer image, which means every algorithm from here on runs three times faster and on cleaner data.

Step two — Histogram Equalization
Now we have a grayscale image, but there's a new problem. The CCPD dataset has images taken in all kinds of conditions — bright sunlight, overcast skies, rain, fog, nighttime. A lot of these images are either too dark or too washed out. If you try to detect edges in a foggy image, everything is kind of a uniform gray and the edges are barely there. There's not enough contrast for Canny to latch onto.
Histogram equalization fixes this by redistributing the brightness values. Here's the intuition: imagine you plot all the pixel values of an image on a bar chart. In a dark, foggy image, almost all the bars would be bunched up on the left side — mostly dark pixels, very few bright ones. Histogram equalization spreads those bars out so they cover the full 0-to-255 range more evenly.
The way it actually works is through the cumulative distribution function of the histogram. You look at each brightness value, count how many pixels are at or below that value, and use that cumulative count to remap the original value to a new, spread-out value. Pixels that were all clustered together in a narrow dark range now get stretched across a wider range, which means the image suddenly has much stronger contrast.
The practical effect for our pipeline is that a plate that was barely visible in foggy conditions now has sharp, high-contrast edges that Canny can easily detect. It's essentially a normalization step that makes all our images behave consistently, regardless of shooting conditions.

Step three — Gaussian Blur
So now the image has good contrast, but there's still a problem before we can do edge detection: noise. Every digital image has it. When a camera captures a scene, the sensor adds random electrical noise. JPEG compression adds its own artifacts. Even a pixel-perfect image has microscopic random variations from pixel to pixel.
Why does this matter? Because edge detection works by looking for sudden changes in brightness. And random noise looks exactly like sudden changes in brightness. A pixel that's supposed to be 120 might randomly be 140, and its neighbor that's supposed to be 122 might be 110. That's a jump of 30 in two pixels — Canny would see that as an edge, even though it's just noise.
Gaussian blur smooths all of that out before we start looking for real edges. The way it works is: for every pixel in the image, instead of keeping its original value, you replace it with a weighted average of it and all its neighbors within a 5×5 window. But not all neighbors are treated equally. The pixel right at the center gets the most weight, and as you move further away the weight drops off following a bell curve — a Gaussian curve, hence the name.
The result is that isolated noisy spikes get averaged away with their neighbors and disappear, while real edges — which span many pixels in a consistent direction — survive the averaging process because all their neighbors are also bright or dark in the same way. You're essentially low-pass filtering the image: keeping the slow, broad changes which are real structures, and removing the fast, sharp pixel-to-pixel fluctuations which are noise.

Step four — Canny Edge Detection
This is the most sophisticated step in the pre-processing chain, and it's doing the real heavy lifting in terms of finding where the license plate is. Canny doesn't just look for brightness changes — it does so in a remarkably precise and intelligent way.
It starts by computing the gradient at every pixel. A gradient just means: how much does the brightness change here, and in which direction? It computes this by running two Sobel filters — one horizontal, one vertical. The horizontal filter detects vertical edges, the vertical filter detects horizontal edges. You combine those two into a single gradient magnitude and direction. So now every pixel has a strength (how sharp is the edge here?) and an angle (which direction does the edge run?).
Then comes non-maximum suppression, which is the step most people don't immediately appreciate. The problem is that even real edges aren't perfectly one pixel wide — they have a bit of spread to them. So instead of a crisp line, you get a thick band of high-gradient pixels. Non-maximum suppression fixes this by looking along the gradient direction at each pixel and asking: are you the strongest point along this direction? If your neighbor in the gradient direction has a higher gradient than you, you get suppressed — set to zero. Only the true peak of each edge survives. This thins every edge down to exactly one pixel wide, giving you beautifully crisp edge lines.
Then comes double thresholding. You provide two values: a high threshold and a low threshold. Any pixel with a gradient above the high threshold is automatically a strong edge — no question, keep it. Any pixel below the low threshold is noise — throw it away. Pixels between the two thresholds are ambiguous — they might be part of a real edge or they might not be.
The final step, hysteresis, resolves that ambiguity. An ambiguous pixel is kept if and only if it is directly connected to a strong edge pixel. The intuition is: real edges don't appear in isolation. If there's a genuine edge nearby and this weak pixel is part of the same contour, it's probably real. If it's just floating by itself with no strong neighbors, it's probably noise. This connection-based decision produces very clean, continuous edge contours rather than the scattered dot pattern you'd get from simple thresholding.
For license plates specifically, this produces strong rectangular outlines around the plate border, plus dense edge activity inside the plate from the characters themselves.

Step five — Morphological Closing
After Canny, we have a problem that's the opposite of what you might expect. We have too many edges, and they're too fragmented. The plate border might be mostly there, but the characters inside — each letter and number — produce their own individual clusters of edge fragments. There are gaps between characters, gaps where contrast was slightly lower, gaps everywhere. If you tried to fit a bounding box to "the plate" right now, you'd fit seven or eight little boxes, not one big one.
Morphological closing fixes this by first making everything bigger and then immediately shrinking it back down. The expansion step is called dilation, and the shrinking step is called erosion.
During dilation, you take a rectangular structuring element — think of it like a stamp — and you stamp it onto every white pixel in the edge image. Everywhere the stamp touches gets turned white. So every edge pixel expands outward in all directions by the size of the stamp, and small gaps between nearby edge clusters get filled in. The characters, which were separate clusters, now start merging into one connected region.
But now everything is puffed up and too big — the plate region has grown beyond its real size. So immediately after, you run erosion, which is the reverse: for every white pixel, you check whether the stamp fits entirely within white pixels. If there's any black pixel under the stamp, that pixel gets turned black. This shrinks all the inflated regions back down to approximately their original size.
The brilliant part is that gaps that got filled during dilation don't come back during erosion. Because once a gap is filled, the surrounding white pixels form a solid region, and erosion can't eat back into a solid interior — it only removes the thin outer edges. So you end up with the same overall shapes, but with all the internal holes and gaps permanently closed.
The shape of the structuring element is critical. We use a rectangle that's much wider than it is tall — something like 17 pixels wide by 5 pixels tall. This matches the aspect ratio of the plate itself. The wide horizontal reach bridges the gaps between characters along the plate. The small vertical size means we don't accidentally merge the plate with something above or below it in the image.

Step six — Contour Detection
Now we have a clean binary image with solid white blobs where potential plate regions are. The job of contour detection is to find and describe the outlines of all those blobs, so we can then reason about their geometry.
OpenCV's findContours scans the binary image systematically and traces the boundary of every connected white region, returning a list of contours where each contour is a sequence of (x, y) points that traces the outline.
Two choices matter here. First, we use RETR_EXTERNAL, which means we only want the outermost boundary of each region. We don't want to trace the inner holes — for example, the hollow center of the letter "O" or "0" would produce an inner contour that we don't care about. Just the outer shell.
Second, we use CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE, which compresses the contours. Instead of storing every single pixel along a straight horizontal or vertical run, it just stores the endpoints. A rectangle that's 200 pixels wide only needs four corner points, not 200 edge pixels. This saves memory and makes the subsequent geometry calculations faster.
At this point we might have anywhere from a handful to hundreds of contours. Most of them are random noise, window frames, road markings, other text in the scene. We need to pick the one that's actually the plate.

Step seven — Geometric Filtering and Scoring
This is the decision-making step. For every contour that came out of the previous step, we compute a bounding rectangle — the smallest axis-aligned rectangle that contains the entire contour. From that rectangle we can extract the width, height, area, position, and the fill ratio — which is the ratio of the actual contour area to the bounding rectangle area. A solid blob has a fill ratio close to 1.0. A wiggly, sparse contour has a low fill ratio.
We then apply hard filters. Any contour that doesn't have a width-to-height ratio between 2 and 6.5 is immediately discarded — license plates are always wider than tall by a significant margin. Any contour that's smaller than 40 by 15 pixels is discarded — too small to be a plate. Anything with less than 1000 total pixels of area is discarded. And anything with a fill ratio below 0.35 is discarded — if it's too sparse and irregular, it can't be a solid plate region.
These hard filters alone eliminate the vast majority of candidates. But there are usually still several survivors, and we need to pick one.
So we score the survivors. A contour gets 2 bonus points if its aspect ratio falls in the ideal range of 2.5 to 5.5, which is the sweet spot for most license plate formats. It gets another 2 points if its width is between 8% and 60% of the total image width — big enough to be a real plate, small enough not to be the entire background. It gets 2 more points if its height is between 3% and 25% of the image height. And it gets a continuous bonus equal to its fill ratio, rewarding compact, well-filled shapes.
The maximum possible score is 7 — which a perfect plate candidate would achieve. The contour with the highest score is returned as the predicted plate location, and a bounding box is drawn around it.